[h1]The text-align Property[/h1]

The text-align property specifies the horizontal alignment of text in an element. By default, text on your website is aligned to the left. However, at times you may require a different alignment. 

text-align property values are as follows: [b]left[/b], [b]right[/b], [b]center[/b], and [b]justify[/b]. 

[b]The HTML:[/b] [code format="html" ]<p class="left">This paragraph is aligned to <strong>left.</strong></p>
<p class="right">This paragraph is aligned to <strong>right.</strong></p>
<p class="center">This paragraph is aligned to <strong>center.</strong></p>[/code]
[b]The CSS:[/b] [code format="css" codeId="521"]p.left {
   text-align:[b] left[/b];
}
p.right {
   text-align:[b] right[/b];
}
p.center {
   text-align:[b] center[/b];
}[/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2597" width="100%"]
[note]When text-align is set to "[b]justify[/b]", each line is stretched so that every line has equal width, and the left and right margins are straight (as in magazines and newspapers).[/note]
